         <abstract id="aspace_974f3521cbbe40993cfaf85af32d43de">The collection primarily documents Stuart's professional work as a Congregational minister (1806-1810) and professor at Andover Theological Seminary (1810-1848).</abstract>
      </did>
      <bioghist id="aspace_a61d8fe01a4668eb40f08d1726af2f87">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Stuart was born in Wilton, Connecticut on March 26, 1780. He graduated from Yale College in 1799 and was ordained on March 5, 1806 after studying with President Timothy Dwight of Yale. Stuart was pastor of First Church, New Haven, CT from 1806 to 1810. He was Professor of Sacred Literature at Andover Theological Seminary from 1810 to 1848.  He died in Andover, MA on January 4, 1852.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_866f73321949635b0c806ba36960dcb2">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The collection is open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_809e219f2196b40b34d94590198eae5f">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>The collection was given to Andover Theological Seminary by Sarah Stuart Robbins (daughter) in 1910 and Mary Stuart Anthony (granddaughter) in 1946. It was transferred from Andover Newton Theological School to the Yale Divinity Library in 2017.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_1d0c90515fcbdfbcb1b5ee8d30040f27">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The bulk of the collection is arranged according to the order prescribed by Stuart in a manuscript dated April 1837, "Expression of my desire, as to the disposal of my Manuscripts, viz. Lectures, Sermons, Essays, etc., which are not published. [Also in regard to the repubublication of some of my works already published]."</p>
         <p>In addition to the items described above, there is some correspondence related to an unsigned review of sermons on the atonement by James Murdock, Daniel Dana and Moses Stuart, which appeared in <title>
               <part>Christian Spectator</part>
            </title>, vol. 9, September 1, 1824. Provenance of this material is not known, although the lettets were discovered with the Edwards Amasa Park Papers. 
Also, there are four letters of the Stuart family, gift of Mary Stuart Anthony.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <prefercite id="aspace_22d7d2ac8113d071802c2533f99e2aa2">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Moses Stuart Papers (RG 294), Special Collections, Yale Divinity School Library</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <arrangement id="aspace_708a03b41e8b0e6c3c20d3e4910057a9">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The collection is organized in three series:</p>
         <p>Series I. Notes, Lectures, Essays</p>
         <p>Series II. Sermons</p>
         <p>Series III. Correspondence</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <altformavail id="aspace_2add980bda749b23a9af2a2b2fd3ea7c">
         <head>Existence and Location of Copies</head>
         <p>5 reels of microfilm: negative 101-105; positive 118-122</p>  
      </altformavail>
